:: UMC05 {"position":"450,225","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "UMC05">>
<<include "header">>
<main>

/*Sound effects */

Oi. You. What are you doing? Yeah, you. I’m talking to you. With that no-good look on your face. You don’t look like you’re from around here, and there’s nothing I don’t like more than something I don’t recognise. Scram.

Wait. Actually. Hang on a second. Maybe you can do me a favour. I’m the constable round these parts, see, and I’ve been tasked with sniffing out troublemakers. Like yourself. No offence. Or not much. But since you’re standing around like a spare part, maybe you can help me out. 

I’m looking for someone. A criminal. Yeah? Goes by the name of Moll Cutpurse. I’ll be honest with you, she’s a freak. Dresses up in men’s clothes, robs them, even smokes a bloody pipe, for God’s sake.

/*A shout breaks out from the other end of the street — a fight is breaking out.*/

What’s that? A fight? Christ.

Listen. If you see her...send her my way, alright? She’s a pain in my arse, to be honest, and it’d do the City a whole bunch of good to have her behind bars once and for all. I’ll compensate you nicely, if you know what I mean. Or maybe I just won’t send you to the nick. Haven’t decided yet. 

Hey! Bobby! Stop that! Put down the cleaver! 
 
/*The Constable’s voice recedes into the background.
From around the corner, another voice.*/ 

Psst. Psst. Hey. Over here.
What were you talking to the Constable for? You’re not a sneak, are you? Come to Limeburner Lane.
Quickly.

/*MAP NEEDED?*/

Good. Alright. You’re not from here, are you? By here, I mean 1610, where I’m from. You look a little too clean and pristine to be from the 17th century, I reckon. Get your bearings quickly, cos I need your help. What did the Constable ask you?

<<button "He wanted me to help him catch a criminal.">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "UMC06">><</button>>

<<button "He was acting kinda weird.">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "UMC06">><</button>>






</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: UMC06 {"position":"450,375","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "UMC06">>
<<include "header">>
<main>

Hmm. He and I go way back. We’ve been doing this dance for years, ever since I was a nipper. You’ve caught on, haven’t you? I’m Moll Cutpurse. I can tell you’re the kinda person who likes to walk on the wild side. I can see it in your eyes...that little glint. You can’t fool me. I’m bringing you onto my team. 
Welcome. First things first: we’ve gotta get you a new name. A pseudonym, if you will. You think Moll Cutpurse is my real name? Nah. It’s actually (she gags a little bit) Mary Frithat. Ugh. Can you imagine? Do I seem like a Mary? The answer is no, before you say anything you might regret.
Pseudonyms are important for criminals. They stop the constables from being able to track you down so easily. So what’s yours? If you shorten your first name and then use a verb for the first half of your surname, and some kind of word for money for the second half — then that’ll be that. So something like...Soph Grabcoin, or Al Takecash. Tell me when you’ve come up with them.


<<button "We've all come up with names.">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "UMC07">><</button>>







</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: UMC07 {"position":"450,525","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "UMC07">>
<<include "header">>
<main>

You done? Excellent. Let’s hear them. Say them out loud. Proudly!

/*Time to say names*/

What a merry band of ne’er-do-wells. Now come on. Let’s get moving. Rule number one — never stand in the same place for too long. Draws attention to yourself. That’s what got you in trouble with the Constable in the first place.

Here’s rule number two — whenever we cross a main road, I’m gonna need you to move quickly — but carefully! I don’t want you getting mown down. Look both ways before you cross. I shouldn’t have to tell you that, but you’d be surprised at how many famous criminals seem to be lacking in basic safety skills. 
We can slow down once we get onto the side streets. Let’s get onto Old Bailey. Find the Central Criminal Court for me, would you?

/*MAP NEEDED*/


<<button "We're at Old Bailey.">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "UMC08">><</button>>







</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: UMC08 {"position":"450,650","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "UMC08">>
<<include "header">>
<main>

Look at that. Huh. She scoffs. You know, I was once brought to one of these places. Not this one — wasn’t as fancy schmancy. I was tried, though, you know. In a court of law. You know why they brought me in? For wearing men’s clothes. Called me “indecent.”  Can you believe it? People spat at me on the street for it. In the end, they made me stand at St Paul’s Cross and wear a white sheet while the priest gave a sermon. I didn’t care much, though. Got a good breeze around the nether regions.

Come on. I don’t want to hang around here too long. Smell of the law gives me the creeps. Let’s head up Giltspur Street. Remember, be quick and careful on main roads.

/*MAP NEEDED*/


<<button "Let's go">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "UMC09">><</button>>







</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: UMC09 {"position":"450,775","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "UMC09">>
<<include "header">>
<main>

Rule number three of becoming the best criminal in the City — stay out of sight as much as possible. That means moving out of the way of any crowds — sticking to the sides of the pavements, avoiding eye contact with big groups — that kind of thing. Make sure you’re doing that as you’re walking. Now, what was I saying? Oh right. The thing is, those lawmen were trying to tell me it was unnatural to wear men’s clothes and smoke a pipe and drink in taverns or whatever else. Unwomanly, or whatever. But it didn’t feel unnatural to me. It just felt...I dunno. I just feel comfortable in men’s stuff. Always have. When I was a kid I’d cut the hem of my dresses so I could move better. Just didn’t feel good in all that fabric. It gets in the way. I can’t run, jump, climb. I was always trying to go and play with the boys, cos the girls didn’t like me much. Every time my aunt tried to get me to sit down and sew, I’d be off like a racehorse. Running and tumbling. The boys didn’t want me near them, though. Even when I’d be locked inside with my threading needle, I’d watch them out the window. Wishing my needle was a dagger. Here, turn onto Cock Lane when you get a chance. And don’t laugh. Or, well, you can laugh.

/*MAP NEEDED*/

<<button "Ok, we turned.">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "UMC10">><</button>>







</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: UMC10 {"position":"450,900","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "UMC10">>
<<include "header">>
<main>

Hang on a second. Something feels a bit funny here.

/*A shimmering sound, and then a sudden crash. */

Moll? That you? 

Ann Duck, as I live and breathe. This is what I meant about time going funny around these parts. This is Ann Duck — notable criminal from 1742.

Notable? Is that any way to describe me? How about the most notorious, most feared, most violent criminal of the last century?

Hmm. There’s already someone occupying that title.

Who? You, my love? Don’t make me laugh. Little miss pickpocket?

Don’t call me that.

Who’s this lot?

Bunch of reprobates I found hanging around Limeburner Lane. I’m showing them the ropes.

First rule of criminality. Stay out of sight.

I’ve already told them that one.

Well, they might not be the brightest bunch. Look, you lot. If you’re gonna make it in this City, you’ve gotta be able to spot others of your ilk. What I want you to do is this — in your little groups, you need to come up with a hand gesture. Nothing rude, mind — that’s too obvious. Just something small. Maybe you’re tipping your cap to someone, or you’re tapping your palm on the back of your hand. Whatever it is, you’re gonna do it to anyone you see on our way to Smithfield Rotunda Garden. If they acknowledge you, great. They’re part of your gang. If not — then no bother. But make sure you keep count of who’s acknowledging you and who isn’t.
Right, come on, you lot. Head onto Smithfield Street.

/*MAP NEEDED*/

<<button "Ok, let's go.">><<set $prevpass to $passage>><<goto "UMC11">><</button>>







</main>
<<include "footer">>


:: UMC11 {"position":"450,1025","size":"100,100"}
<<set $passage to "UMC11">>
<<include "header">>
<main>

Don’t tell them what to do. That’s my job. You lot need to find Snow Hill and head up, turning right onto Smithfield Street, then right again onto Hosier Street, and then left.

Towards the Smithfield Rotunda. Got it? Go on, then. Make sure you’re doing your hand signals.

/*MAP NEEDED*/

What are you doing here, anyway?

Hmm, dunno. Something felt a bit funny. Had a feeling you were up to no good, and wherever there’s mischief, I’ve got to follow. What have you been doing, Moll? It’s been a while. Still cutting men’s purse strings? Small fry, but someone’s got to do it, I suppose.

Made a good amount last week, I’ll have you know.

Don’t be so small-time. You’re a glorified pickpocket at best. And you’re a fence. Even worse! People do their work through you, but you don’t get your hands dirty. Me? People are actually afraid of me. Last week I nearly cut a lad’s finger off cos he wouldn’t give me any of his gold. Week before that I beat a man with glass bottles until he cried for his mother.

You’ll get in trouble one day, Ann Duck. Mark my words.

Nonsense. I’ve been tried 19 times and they ain’t got a thing on me. You need to hang around the ports, Moll. That’s where the good stuff is.

Yeah, I know. But I’m not like you, Ann. I don’t want to beat anyone up. Not unless I have to. Not unless they’re coming for me. I like to keep it quiet. Steal away into the night. A ghost on the streets.

Ah, you don’t get it, Moll. Never have. This lot? The ones who swan around the ports in their furs and their horses with the sleek coats...they don’t care about us. They already rob us every single day! 

Wouldn’t piss on us if we were on fire. Would step over our bodies and wrinkle their noses if they got our blood on their slippers. We’ve gotta make it work for us, Moll. What’s the issue if there’s a bit of violence, here or there? There’s nothing I’ve done that they wouldn’t do to us. Only difference is, they’d get their hired thugs to do it. 

Here, we’re nearly at Smithfield Rotunda Garden, and I’ve got to go. Word is there’s a fancy carriage coming down from Farringdon. See you, Moll. And you lot — don’t get into any trouble. Or not much, anyway.

Bye, Ann!

/*Ann disappears with a shimmer.*/

Thank God she’s gone. Every day’s a competition with Ann Duck.
Right. This will be a good place for a rest. Well? What are your tallies? How many other gang members did you spot?

